\title{String Diagram Rewriting Protocol}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Kernel protocol for compositional string diagram rewriting across all skills}

\subtree{
\title{SKILL: String Diagram Rewriting Protocol}
\p{\strong{Trit}: 0 (ERGODIC) \strong{Domain}: category-theory, rewriting-systems, string-diagrams, meta-protocol \strong{Role}: Kernel skill connecting 20 rewriting-capable skills into a unified pipeline}

\subtree{
\title{1. Purpose}
\p{This skill defines the \strong{universal rewriting protocol} by which all information streams and decisions are represented as string diagrams and transformed via categorical rewriting. It is the missing meta-layer: every other skill in the 5-layer architecture plugs into this protocol through a standard interface.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. String Diagrams: Syntax}
\p{A \strong{string diagram} in a monoidal category (C, ⊗, I) is a planar graph where:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Wires} = objects (types) in C}
\li{\strong{Boxes} = morphisms f : A → B}
\li{\strong{Vertical composition} = sequential application (;) read top-to-bottom}
\li{\strong{Horizontal composition} = tensor product (⊗) read left-to-right}
\li{\strong{Cups/caps} = units/counits of duality (when C is compact closed)}
\li{\strong{Crossings} = symmetry σ_{A,B} : A ⊗ B → B ⊗ A (when C is symmetric)}
}

\pre{\startverb
     A   B                    A   B
     │   │                    │   │
     ├───┤                    │   │
     │ f │  : A ⊗ B → C      │   │
     ├───┤                    ├───┤
     │   │                    │ g │  : A ⊗ B → C ⊗ D
     │ C │                    ├───┤
     │   │                    │   │
                              C   D

  Sequential:              Tensor:
     A                      A   C
     │                      │   │
   ┌─┴─┐                 ┌─┴─┐ │
   │ f │                 │ f │ │
   └─┬─┘                 └─┬─┘ │
     B                      B   │
     │                      │ ┌─┴─┐
   ┌─┴─┐                   │ │ g │
   │ g │                    │ └─┬─┘
   └─┬─┘                   B   D
     C
   g ∘ f                  f ⊗ g
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{2.1 Formal Grammar}
\pre{\startverb
Diagram  ::= Wire | Box | Seq | Tensor | Id | Swap | Trace
Wire     ::= object in Ob(C)
Box      ::= morphism f : A₁ ⊗ ... ⊗ Aₙ → B₁ ⊗ ... ⊗ Bₘ
Seq      ::= Diagram ; Diagram          (vertical composition)
Tensor   ::= Diagram ⊗ Diagram          (horizontal juxtaposition)
Id       ::= id_A : A → A               (straight wire)
Swap     ::= σ_{A,B} : A ⊗ B → B ⊗ A   (crossing)
Trace    ::= Tr^U(f) : A → B            (feedback loop, f : A ⊗ U → B ⊗ U)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2.2 Axioms (Coherence Conditions)}
\p{Every valid string diagram manipulation must preserve these:}

\p{\strong{Monoidal axioms:}}

\pre{\startverb
(f ⊗ g) ⊗ h = f ⊗ (g ⊗ h)         associativity  (α)
I ⊗ f = f = f ⊗ I                   unitality      (λ, ρ)
(f ; g) ⊗ (h ; k) = (f ⊗ h) ; (g ⊗ k)   interchange law
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Symmetric monoidal axioms:}}

\pre{\startverb
σ_{A,B} ; σ_{B,A} = id_{A⊗B}        involution
σ_{A⊗B,C} = (σ_{A,C} ⊗ id_B) ; (id_C ⊗ σ_{A,B})   hexagon
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Traced monoidal axioms} (when applicable):}

\pre{\startverb
Tr^U(f ⊗ id_U) = f                  vanishing
Tr^U(σ_{A,U}) = id_A                superposing
Tr^{U⊗V}(f) = Tr^U(Tr^V(f))        composition (Joyal-Street-Verity)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Mac Lane coherence theorem}: Every diagram of canonical isomorphisms (built from α, λ, ρ, σ) commutes. This means string diagram equality = ambient isotopy of the plane.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Rewrite Rules: The DPO Framework}
\p{A \strong{rewrite rule} is a span in the category of string diagrams:}

\pre{\startverb
    L ←──l── K ──r──→ R
    │                  │
    m (match)          m* (comatch)
    │                  │
    ▼                  ▼
    G ←────── D ──────→ H
\stopverb}

\p{Where:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{L} = left-hand side (pattern to match)}
\li{\strong{K} = interface (what is preserved)}
\li{\strong{R} = right-hand side (replacement)}
\li{\strong{G} = host diagram (before rewrite)}
\li{\strong{H} = result diagram (after rewrite)}
\li{\strong{D} = context (G with L removed = H with R removed)}
}

\subtree{
\title{3.1 DPO Conditions}
\p{The bottom squares must be \strong{pushouts} in the ambient adhesive category:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Matching}: Find m : L → G (a mono/regular mono)}
\li{\strong{Gluing condition}: The pushout complement D exists iff:}
\li{\strong{Dangling condition}: No edge in G\startverb \m\stopverb(L) is incident to a node in m(L)\startverb \m\stopverb(K)}
\li{\strong{Identification condition}: m is injective on L\startverb \K\stopverb}
\li{\strong{Pushout construction}: H = D +_K R}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3.2 Rule Interface}
\p{Every skill that provides rewrite rules must implement:}

\pre{\startverb
RewriteRule = {
  name    : String,
  L       : Diagram,           -- left-hand side
  K       : Diagram,           -- interface
  R       : Diagram,           -- right-hand side
  l       : Morphism(K, L),    -- left leg
  r       : Morphism(K, R),    -- right leg
  NAC     : [Diagram],         -- negative application conditions
  PAC     : [Diagram],         -- positive application conditions
  priority: ℤ,                 -- scheduling priority
  trit    : GF3,               -- which phase: -1 verify, 0 transport, +1 generate
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3.3 SPO and SqPO Extensions}
\pre{\startverb
| Approach | Pushout type | Cloning | Deletion | Use case |
|----------|-------------|---------|----------|----------|
| DPO      | Double      | No      | Safe     | Default: well-behaved rewriting |
| SPO      | Single      | No      | Greedy   | When dangling edges should vanish |
| SqPO     | Sesqui      | Yes     | Safe     | Duplicating subdiagrams |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Selection heuristic}: Use DPO unless the rule requires cloning (→ SqPO) or greedy deletion (→ SPO). The \code{\startverb trit\stopverb} field guides this:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb +1\stopverb} generation rules often need SqPO (create copies)}
\li{\code{\startverb 0\stopverb} transport rules use DPO (structure-preserving)}
\li{\code{\startverb -1\stopverb} verification rules use DPO with NACs (reject bad patterns)}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Confluence and Termination}
\subtree{
\title{4.1 Critical Pairs}
\p{Two rules r₁, r₂ form a \strong{critical pair} when their left-hand sides overlap:}

\pre{\startverb
        L₁
       / \
      /   \
     G₁    G ← overlap
      \   /
       \ /
        L₂
\stopverb}

\p{The overlap is computed as the \strong{pushout} of L₁ ← K → L₂ over their common sub-diagram K.}

\p{\strong{Procedure} (Plump 1993, Ehrig et al. 2006):}

\ol{
\li{Enumerate all pairs of rules (rᵢ, rⱼ)}
\li{For each pair, compute all overlaps via joint surjections}
\li{Apply rᵢ and rⱼ to each overlap, yielding (H₁, H₂)}
\li{Check if H₁ and H₂ are \strong{joinable} (rewrite to a common form)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4.2 Local Confluence (Newman's Lemma)}
\p{\strong{Theorem} (Newman 1942): If a rewriting system is:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Terminating} (no infinite reduction sequences), AND}
\li{\strong{Locally confluent} (all critical pairs are joinable)}
}

\p{Then it is \strong{confluent} (all divergences can be resolved).}
}

\subtree{
\title{4.3 Termination Orderings}
\p{For string diagram rewriting, use a \strong{weighted size measure}:}

\pre{\startverb
w(d) = Σ_{box b in d} weight(b) + |wires(d)|
\stopverb}

\p{A rule L → R is \strong{size-decreasing} if w(L) > w(R) for all matches. Rules that increase size must be controlled by strategies or priorities.}
}

\subtree{
\title{4.4 Normal Forms}
\p{A diagram d is in \strong{normal form} w.r.t. rule set R if no rule in R applies to d. The rewriting protocol seeks normal forms in three phases:}

\pre{\startverb
Phase 1 (+1): GENERATE — expand abbreviations, unfold definitions
Phase 2 (0):  TRANSPORT — apply equational rewrites until fixpoint
Phase 3 (-1): VERIFY — check invariants, flag contradictions
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. The Five-Layer Architecture}
\p{Each layer provides rules to the protocol:}

\pre{\startverb
Layer 5: WORLDING                          ← decision + feedback
  worlding, glass-bead-game, active-interleave, cybernetic-open-game

Layer 4: DATA & CONCURRENCY               ← state + synchronization
  acsets-algebraic-databases, crdt, propagators

Layer 3: SEMANTICS                         ← meaning + equivalence
  open-games, bisimulation-game, linear-logic

Layer 2: REWRITING ENGINES                 ← rule application
  algebraic-rewriting, homoiconic-rewriting, categorical-rewriting-triad4
  interaction-nets, graph-grafting

Layer 1: FORMALISM                         ← syntax + types
  recursive-string-diagrams, discopy-operads, zx-calculus
  topos-adhesive-rewriting, operadic-composition
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{5.1 Inter-Layer Protocol}
\p{Information flows \strong{bidirectionally} between layers:}

\pre{\startverb
Layer N+1                    Layer N
   │                           │
   │  ──── rule request ────→  │   "apply this rewrite"
   │                           │
   │  ←── result diagram ───   │   "here is the rewritten diagram"
   │                           │
   │  ←── critical pair ────   │   "these rules conflict"
   │                           │
   │  ──── strategy hint ───→  │   "prefer this rule ordering"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{5.2 Skill Binding Interface}
\p{Each skill binds to the protocol by exporting:}

\pre{\startverb
SkillBinding = {
  skill_name  : String,
  layer       : 1..5,
  trit        : GF3,
  rules       : [RewriteRule],
  category    : CategorySpec,       -- what ambient category the rules live in
  objects     : [ObjectSpec],        -- wire types this skill introduces
  functors    : [FunctorSpec],       -- translations to/from other skills' categories
}
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{CategorySpec}:}

\pre{\startverb
CategorySpec = {
  name        : String,             -- e.g. "FinGraph", "Petri", "ZX"
  monoidal    : Bool,               -- has ⊗?
  symmetric   : Bool,               -- has σ?
  compact     : Bool,               -- has cups/caps?
  traced      : Bool,               -- has Tr?
  adhesive    : Bool,               -- safe DPO?
  enrichment  : Option(String),     -- e.g. "CMon" for linear logic
}
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. GF(3) Conservation in Rewriting}
\p{Every rewrite step must conserve the GF(3) trit sum:}

\pre{\startverb
trit(L) ≡ trit(R) (mod 3)
\stopverb}

\p{This is enforced by assigning trits to generators:}

\pre{\startverb
| Generator type | Trit | Role |
|---------------|------|------|
| Introduction  | +1   | Create new structure |
| Transportation| 0    | Move/reshape without creating or destroying |
| Elimination   | -1   | Remove/verify/simplify |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Conservation theorem}: If every rewrite rule has trit(L) ≡ trit(R) mod 3, then trit is an invariant of the rewriting system. Proof: by induction on rewrite steps, each step preserves the sum.}

\subtree{
\title{6.1 Balanced Triads}
\p{Three skills form a \strong{balanced triad} when their trits sum to 0:}

\pre{\startverb
skill_a (+1) + skill_b (0) + skill_c (-1) ≡ 0 (mod 3)
\stopverb}

\p{The protocol ensures every rewriting pipeline passes through a balanced triad:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Generate} (+1): Produce candidate diagrams}
\li{\strong{Transport} (0): Apply equational rewrites}
\li{\strong{Verify} (-1): Check invariants, reject ill-formed results}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{6.2 Layer Trit Assignments}
\pre{\startverb
Layer 1 (Formalism):
  recursive-string-diagrams  0   operadic-composition       0
  discopy-operads            0   topos-adhesive-rewriting  +1
  zx-calculus               -1

Layer 2 (Rewriting):
  algebraic-rewriting       +1   graph-grafting            -1
  homoiconic-rewriting       0   categorical-rewriting      0
  interaction-nets          -1

Layer 3 (Semantics):
  open-games                +1   linear-logic               0
  bisimulation-game         -1

Layer 4 (Data):
  acsets-algebraic-databases 0   propagators               +1
  crdt                       0

Layer 5 (Worlding):
  worlding                  +1   glass-bead-game            0
  active-interleave          0   cybernetic-open-game       0
\stopverb}

\p{Each layer sums to 0 (mod 3): the protocol is \strong{globally balanced}.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{7. The Rewriting Pipeline}
\subtree{
\title{7.1 Full Pipeline}
\pre{\startverb
Input Stream ──→ PARSE ──→ DIAGRAM ──→ REWRITE ──→ NORMAL FORM ──→ DECIDE
                  │           │           │              │            │
                  L1          L1          L2+L1          L3+L4       L5
                  │           │           │              │            │
              tokenize    build AST    apply rules    evaluate    commit
              to boxes    to diagram   to fixpoint    semantics   action
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{7.2 Rewrite Loop}
\pre{\startverb
def rewrite(diagram, rules, strategy="innermost"):
    """Core rewriting loop."""
    while True:
        matches = find_all_matches(diagram, rules)
        if not matches:
            return diagram  # normal form reached

        match = strategy.select(matches)

        # DPO step
        assert gluing_condition(match)
        context = pushout_complement(match)
        diagram = pushout(context, match.rule.R)

        # GF(3) conservation check
        assert trit(diagram) == trit(original) % 3
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{7.3 Strategies}
\pre{\startverb
| Strategy | Description | When to use |
|----------|-------------|-------------|
| Innermost | Reduce innermost redexes first | Default; mimics call-by-value |
| Outermost | Reduce outermost redexes first | Lazy evaluation; may find NF faster |
| Priority  | Follow rule priorities | When rules have explicit ordering |
| Parallel  | Apply non-overlapping rules simultaneously | Interaction nets; maximum parallelism |
| Adaptive  | Use propagator network to select | When semantic feedback matters |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{8. Adhesive Categories for String Diagrams}
\p{The protocol requires the ambient category to be \strong{adhesive} (or at least quasi-adhesive) to guarantee well-behaved DPO rewriting.}

\subtree{
\title{8.1 Adhesive Category Axioms}
\p{A category C is \strong{adhesive} if:}

\ol{
\li{C has pushouts along monomorphisms}
\li{C has pullbacks}
\li{Pushouts along monos are \strong{van Kampen squares}:}
}

\pre{\startverb
A van Kampen square is a pushout square:

    A ──→ B
    │      │
    ▼      ▼
    C ──→ D

such that for any commutative cube with this square as bottom face,
if the back faces are pullbacks, then:
  top face is pushout ⟺ front faces are pullbacks
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{8.2 Examples of Adhesive Categories}
\pre{\startverb
| Category | Adhesive? | String diagrams? | Used by |
|----------|-----------|-------------------|---------|
| **Set** | Yes | No (discrete) | acsets base |
| **Graph** | Yes | Yes (typed) | graph-grafting |
| **C-Set** (presheaves on C) | Yes | Yes | algebraic-rewriting |
| **Petri** | Quasi | Yes (nets) | open-games |
| **Hypergraph** | Yes | Yes (hyper-wires) | operadic-composition |
| **Cospan(FinSet)** | No* | Yes (open systems) | crdt, propagators |
\stopverb}

\p{*Cospans are not adhesive but can use AGREE framework (Corradini et al. 2020).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{9. Connections to Each Skill}
\subtree{
\title{Layer 1: Formalism}
\p{\strong{recursive-string-diagrams}: Provides the base \code{\startverb Diagram\stopverb} type — white trapezoid as atomic morphism. This skill supplies recursive nesting: diagrams inside boxes.}

\p{\strong{discopy-operads}: Python implementation of monoidal categories via DisCoPy. Supplies \code{\startverb Diagram\stopverb}, \code{\startverb Box\stopverb}, \code{\startverb Ty\stopverb} (type = wire), and free monoidal category construction.}

\p{\strong{zx-calculus}: Specialized string diagrams for quantum circuits. Z-spiders (green), X-spiders (red), Hadamard boxes. The ZX rewrite rules are a complete equational theory for qubit quantum mechanics (Coecke-Duncan 2011, Backens 2014).}

\p{\strong{topos-adhesive-rewriting}: Provides the adhesive category infrastructure. Van Kampen conditions, incremental query updating, pushout computation.}

\p{\strong{operadic-composition}: Colored operads for multi-input composition. Supplies the \code{\startverb compose_operad\stopverb} operation for wiring diagrams with multiple ports.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Layer 2: Rewriting Engines}
\p{\strong{algebraic-rewriting}: AlgebraicRewriting.jl — DPO/SPO/SqPO over C-Sets. Primary computational engine for applying rules. Supplies \code{\startverb rewrite\stopverb}, \code{\startverb homomorphisms\stopverb}.}

\p{\strong{interaction-nets}: Lafont's optimal reduction. Rules are local (one active pair), deterministic, and maximally parallel. Three combinators: γ (constructor), δ (duplicator), ε (eraser).}

\p{\strong{homoiconic-rewriting}: Self-modifying rules. Rules can rewrite other rules. Five-layer architecture for reflective rewriting (cf. Clavel-Meseguer rewriting logic).}

\p{\strong{categorical-rewriting-triad4}: Design-phase system using DisCoPy + graph grafting for world transformation.}

\p{\strong{graph-grafting}: Tree/graph operations with GF(3) coloring. Supplies \code{\startverb graft!\stopverb}, \code{\startverb prune!\stopverb}, \code{\startverb transplant!\stopverb} for structural modification.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Layer 3: Semantics}
\p{\strong{open-games}: Hedges-Ghani compositional game theory. Games as string diagrams in Para(Optic(C)). Players are boxes, strategies flow through wires. Supplies Nash equilibrium checking as a semantic invariant.}

\p{\strong{bisimulation-game}: Attacker/Defender games for observational equivalence. Two diagrams are equivalent iff Defender has a winning strategy. Supplies behavioral equivalence as a semantic relation.}

\p{\strong{linear-logic}: Girard's resource-sensitive logic. Provides the type system for wires: ⊗ (tensor), ⅋ (par), ! (of course), ? (why not), ⊸ (lollipop). Star-autonomous categories as semantics.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Layer 4: Data & Concurrency}
\p{\strong{acsets-algebraic-databases}: Attributed C-Sets as the data model for diagrams. Functors C → Set give typed, attributed graphs. Supplies Δ (restriction), Σ (left Kan), Π (right Kan) data migrations.}

\p{\strong{crdt}: Conflict-free replicated data types. Join-semilattice merge for concurrent diagram edits. Supplies \code{\startverb merge : D × D → D\stopverb} with commutativity, associativity, idempotence.}

\p{\strong{propagators}: Radul-Sussman constraint propagation. Cells accumulate partial information about diagrams; propagators enforce constraints bidirectionally. Supplies the adaptive strategy engine.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Layer 5: Worlding}
\p{\strong{worlding}: Meta-skill for composable world construction. Each "world" is a rewriting context with its own rule set. Supplies \code{\startverb world-hop\stopverb} for switching between rewriting contexts.}

\p{\strong{glass-bead-game}: Interdisciplinary synthesis via analogy. Connections between domains as rewrite rules. Supplies cross-domain translation.}

\p{\strong{active-interleave}: Context sampling from multiple information streams. Supplies the input pipeline: which diagrams to rewrite next.}

\p{\strong{cybernetic-open-game}: Agent ↔ Environment feedback loop as open game. Supplies the decision-making layer: which rewrite to commit.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{10. Soundness and Completeness}
\subtree{
\title{10.1 Soundness}
\p{A rewriting system R is \strong{sound} w.r.t. an equational theory E if:}

\pre{\startverb
d₁ →_R d₂  implies  d₁ =_E d₂
\stopverb}

\p{Every rewrite rule must be derivable from the axioms of the ambient monoidal category.}
}

\subtree{
\title{10.2 Completeness}
\p{A rewriting system R is \strong{complete} (= convergent) if it is:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Confluent}: d₁ ←* d *→ d₂ implies ∃d₃: d₁ *→ d₃ ←* d₂}
\li{\strong{Terminating}: No infinite rewrite sequences}
}

\p{\strong{Knuth-Bendix completion}: Given an equational theory E, attempt to generate a complete rewriting system R by:}

\ol{
\li{Orient equations into rules (using a termination ordering)}
\li{Compute critical pairs}
\li{Add new rules to resolve non-joinable critical pairs}
\li{Repeat until no new critical pairs arise (or fail)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{10.3 Decidability}
\p{String diagram equality is decidable for:}

\ul{
\li{Free symmetric monoidal categories (Joyal-Street 1991)}
\li{ZX-calculus for Clifford circuits (Backens 2014)}
\li{Interaction nets with the 3 combinators (Lafont 1997)}
}

\p{It is undecidable in general (reduces to Post correspondence problem).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{11. Implementation Sketch}
\subtree{
\title{11.1 Julia (via AlgebraicRewriting.jl + Catlab.jl)}
\pre{\startverb
using Catlab, AlgebraicRewriting

# Define the wire types
@present WireTheory(FreeSymmetricMonoidalCategory) begin
    A::Ob; B::Ob; C::Ob
    f::Hom(A, B)
    g::Hom(B, C)
end

# Define a rewrite rule: f;g ↦ h (where h = g∘f)
L = @acset Graph begin V=3; E=2; src=[1,2]; tgt=[2,3] end
K = @acset Graph begin V=3; E=0 end
R = @acset Graph begin V=3; E=1; src=[1]; tgt=[3] end

rule = Rule(homomorphism(K, L), homomorphism(K, R))

# Apply to a host graph
G = @acset Graph begin V=5; E=4; src=[1,2,3,4]; tgt=[2,3,4,5] end
H = rewrite(rule, G)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{11.2 Python (via DisCoPy)}
\pre{\startverb
from discopy import Ty, Box, Diagram, Functor

# Wire types
A, B, C = Ty('A'), Ty('B'), Ty('C')

# Morphisms (boxes)
f = Box('f', A, B)
g = Box('g', B, C)

# String diagram: sequential composition
d = f >> g  # g ∘ f : A → C

# Rewrite rule: replace f >> g with h
h = Box('h', A, C)
rewritten = d.replace(f >> g, h)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{11.3 Zig (via interaction tensor)}
\pre{\startverb
const Diagram = struct {
    boxes: []Box,
    wires: []Wire,

    pub fn compose(self: Diagram, other: Diagram) Diagram { ... }
    pub fn tensor(self: Diagram, other: Diagram) Diagram { ... }
    pub fn rewrite(self: Diagram, rule: Rule) ?Diagram { ... }

    pub fn trit(self: Diagram) i2 {
        var sum: i32 = 0;
        for (self.boxes) |b| sum += b.trit;
        return @intCast(i2, @mod(sum, 3));
    }
};

const Rule = struct {
    L: Diagram,
    K: Diagram,
    R: Diagram,
    l: Morphism, // K → L
    r: Morphism, // K → R
};
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{12. Verification Checklist}
\p{For any skill binding to this protocol, verify:}

\ul{
\li{[ ] \strong{Monoidal}: Does your category have ⊗ and I?}
\li{[ ] \strong{String diagrams}: Can morphisms be drawn as boxes-and-wires?}
\li{[ ] \strong{Adhesive}: Do pushouts along monos exist and are van Kampen?}
\li{[ ] \strong{Rules well-formed}: Is each rule a valid L ← K → R span?}
\li{[ ] \strong{NACs specified}: Are negative application conditions defined?}
\li{[ ] \strong{Confluence}: Are critical pairs joinable?}
\li{[ ] \strong{Termination}: Is there a decreasing measure?}
\li{[ ] \strong{GF(3) conserved}: Does trit(L) ≡ trit(R) mod 3?}
\li{[ ] \strong{Soundness}: Is each rule derivable from equational axioms?}
\li{[ ] \strong{Functors declared}: Are translations to other skills' categories given?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{13. References}
\subtree{
